Holy shit, you are so niave!<br>
<br>
Store chains spend millions in researching what makes buyers spend money. They also know problem groups who are suseptible (impulse buyers, depression shoppers, low income people with poor budget skills) and target those groups. Every song that comes over the PA, every store display, every print ad, is based of research of how they can manipulate the buyer to blow his wad before he leaves the store.<br>
<br>
If EQ wasn't designed to be addictive, why would people spend 36 hours straight camping items? How many PS2 gamers play that long against a computer opponent in one sitting?<br>
<br>
If EQ wasn't designed to be addictive, why there people with well over 200 days played? Do you realize that 200 days is 4,800 hours played?<br>
<br>
The numbers are too large to say this out of the norm for the playerbase. Now maybe we are all freaks, but EQ certainly knew how to target us and draw us into their world... and I highly doubt it was by accident. <p><br>
