I already explained this.  It is because of the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   community</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, the competition that helps to feed, and the strong bonds people form between each other.  I had 115 days played on Hayzen over 2.5 years.  The very first day I played it I spent eight hours creating different characters, trying to come up with a name I liked, and then leveling Hayzen to level 5.  I thought the game was SO COOL.  You know what, though?  I spent almost the same amount of time playing the first time I popped Final Fantasy VIII into my Playstation.<br>
<br>
The loot and big monsters are fun, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   but only because there are people there to share the experience with</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  Without the people it would mean jack squat.  When you're finished the with Playstation 2 game there is nobody to say goodbye to.  There is nobody that you've come to know that you may feel an obligation twoards.  You just turn the game off.  Why do you think there are so many people, just from our little forum, that continue hanging around and participating in the forums, in thier guild boards, even after they've stopped playing the game?  It certainly isn't because EverQuest is addictive, otherwise they would be playing still don't you think?  But they don't.  They stop playing, yet continue being a part of the COMMUNITY.<br>
<br>
Yes, the fact that the game never ends is part of the reason people <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   initially</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> spend enough time together to form these bonds.  But what do you expect from an online <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   persistent</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> world.  That's the entire point of an MMOG.  Just as it is the entire point of a retail store to sell merchandise and make money.<br>
<br>
You keep repeating that the glaring sign that EverQuest is addictive is that people spend so much time doing it.  However you keep completley glossing over the fact that there are a lot of people that spend just as much time hanging out at bars, going to clubs, and a myriad of other social situations. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uhayzen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Hayzen</A> at: 10/20/02 8:32:55 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uloeganwolfheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Loegan Wolfheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Please do things my way, thx.</span><br>  Posts: 1670<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/20/02 8:42:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=247.topic&index=54>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://loegan.homestead.com/files/rn.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EverQuest and Addiction</span><hr size=1> The point is that people would not spend such enormous amounts of time and effort if the game was not addictive. A non-addictive game just couldn't instill the desire in them to do so. If people were just in it for the community, there are alot of chat programs that use avatars and virtual worlds and don't require camping items for 8-36 hours. <p><br>
