<br>
Now the shopping thing. the retailers intent is for you to blow all the money you can. they spend massive amounts of money to keep you spending more time in their stores, spending more money on things, and coming back for more. they want it to be addictive. hell that means for $$$ for them. i know this from personal experience because i used to be a stocker for a grocery store. we used to spend all weekend setting up displays and rearranging them to get the customer to buy more. management would have meetings like every other day to figure out how to keep the customer in the store longer. best way they could do this was product placement. ever notice that your bread and milk are on opposite sides of the store? that's done on purpose. i don't think shopping in itself is addicting but the retailers intent is to make it so. <p><p align="center"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=414061">Hadena Rtehpwn 57 High Elf Weezard</a></p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uhayzen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Hayzen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 264<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/20/02 9:02:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=247.topic&index=56>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EverQuest and Addiction</span><hr size=1> To be human is to be naturally dependant, and I believe that most people are empathetic towards this.  How many times did you help someone in your guild when there was nothing in it for you?  I did it many, many times and happily so.  Sometimes I felt an obligation to go to a raid or help with a quest, because I had made a commitment to these people.  Other times I played because I felt an obligation to people, because in the past they had spent their money, and time, and helped me achieve a goal in the game.  Just as I sometimes feel I am obligated towards my friends and family outside of the game.<br>
<br>
How often do people in chat rooms help each other achieve goals like that?  How many chatrooms do you know of that it takes more than one person to accomplish that goal?  EverQuest is not <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   just</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the community, it makes up a very large percentage of the game for sure, but there are goals to be accomplished. But, the community is the driving force behind people wanting to accomplish those goals.<br>
<br>
I'm a huge BattleTech fan, and before EverQuest I played a game called MechCommander.  This is a real time strategy game based on the BattleTech universe.  The game is primarly a single player game, but it had a multiplayer feature.  I played in a ladder league called Starlance, in a Clan (a guild) called The Jade Falcons.  Starlance was basically a web based tournament league created by a fellow player; I think it may still be around I'm not sure.  I spent 1.5 years playing that game, about 8 hours per week.  Want to know why?  Because of the PEOPLE.  It was fun being a member of the Clan and competing against the other groups to earn points.  I didn't spend as much time with that game as EverQuest because multiplayer consisted of many short games, usually lasting about 20 - 60 minutes on average.  But that game also was not marketed, or designed, to be a persistent world.  I stopped playing that game about four years ago, and do you want to hear something crazy?  I'm still in contact with almost everyone from my MechCommander group.<br>
<br>
Yesterday I spent four hours reading a novel.  The day before that I'm sure I spent at least two.  It's a great book, and I enjoy it a lot.  I still have at least 1000 pages to go, and it may take me upwards of another twenty hours of reading to finish it.  I'll probably get to the end within the next few days.  Do you think I may be addicted to that book?<br>
<br>
Time spent on an activity is not a measure of addiction.<br>
<br>
